name: 3-amino-1h-pyrazole-4-carbonitrile
Reason: Basic unit, pyrazole, typically has a melting point in the range of 70 to 100 degrees Celsius. The amino group (-NH2) generally increases the melting point due to the ability to form intermolecular hydrogen bonds, potentially adding +20 to +50 degrees. The nitrile group (-C≡N) is electron-withdrawing and can also participate in dipole-dipole interactions, possibly adding +10 to +30 degrees. Each group's effects might not be simply additive due to potential intramolecular interactions, but for this estimation we'll consider an additive model.
Prediction: Based on the above, the predicted melting point would be: 100 (high end for basic pyrazole unit) + 50 (maximum expected for the amino group) + 30 (maximum expected for the nitrile group) = 180 degrees Celsius.
